{"indexed":{"date-parts":[[2025,4,19]],"date-time":"2025-04-19T13:47:11Z","timestamp":1745070431169},"reference-count":88,"publisher":"Wiley","issue":"5","license":[{"start":{"date-parts":[[2022,2,27]],"date-time":"2022-02-27T00:00:00Z","timestamp":1645920000000},"content-version":"vor","delay-in-days":0,"URL":"http:\/\/onlinelibrary.wiley.com\/termsAndConditions#vor"}],"funder":[{"DOI":"10.13039\/501100001809","name":"National Natural Science Foundation of China","doi-asserted-by":"publisher","award":["31970437"],"id":[{"id":"10.13039\/501100001809","id-type":"DOI","asserted-by":"publisher"}]}],"content-domain":{"domain":["onlinelibrary.wiley.com"],"crossmark-restriction":true},"published-print":{"date-parts":[[2022,7]]},"abstract":"<jats:title>Abstract<\/jats:title><jats:p>Eriophyoid mites (Acari: Eriophyoidea) are among the smallest of terrestrial arthropods and the most species\u2010rich group of herbivorous mites with a high host specificity. However, knowledge of their species diversity has been impeded by the difficulty of their morphological differentiation. This study assembles a DNA barcode reference library that includes 1850\u00a0mitochondrial COI sequences which provides coverage for 45% of the 930\u00a0species of eriophyoid mites known from China, and for 37\u00a0North American species. Sequence analysis showed a clear barcode gap in nearly all species, reflecting the fact that intraspecific divergences averaged 0.97% versus a mean of 18.51% for interspecific divergences (minimum nearest\u2010neighbour distances) in taxa belonging to three families. Based on these results, we used DNA barcoding to explore the species diversity of eriophyoid mites as well as their host interactions. The 1850\u00a0sequences were assigned to 531\u00a0barcode index numbers (BINs). Analyses examining the correspondence between these BINs and species identifications based on morphology revealed that members of 45\u00a0species were assigned to two or more BINs, resulting in 1.16 times more BINs than morphospecies. Richness projections suggest that over 2345 BINs occurred at the sampled locations. Host plant analysis showed that 89% of these mites (BINs) attack only one or two congeneric host species, but the others have several hosts. Furthermore, host\u2010mite network analyses demonstrate that eriophyoid mites are high host\u2010specific, and modularity is high in plant\u2010mite networks. By creating a highly effective identification system for eriophyoid mites in the Barcode of Life Data Systems database (BOLD), DNA barcoding will advance our understanding of the diversity of eriophyoid mites and their host interactions.<\/jats:p>","DOI":"10.1111\/1755-0998.13599","type":"journal-article","created":{"date-parts":[[2022,2,18]],"date-time":"2022-02-18T08:18:38Z","timestamp":1645172318000},"page":"1986-1998","update-policy":"http:\/\/dx.doi.org\/10.1002\/crossmark_policy","source":"Crossref","is-referenced-by-count":24,"title":"DNA barcoding uncovers cryptic diversity in minute herbivorous mites (Acari, Eriophyoidea)","prefix":"10.1111","volume":"22","author":[{"given":"Yue","family":"Yin","sequence":"first","affiliation":[{"name":"Department of Entomology Nanjing Agricultural University  Nanjing China"},{"name":"Centre for Biodiversity Genomics University of Guelph  Guelph Ontario Canada"}]},{"given":"Liang\u2010Fei","family":"Yao","sequence":"additional","affiliation":[{"name":"Department of Entomology Nanjing Agricultural University  Nanjing China"}]},{"given":"Yue","family":"Hu","sequence":"additional","affiliation":[{"name":"Department of Entomology Nanjing Agricultural University  Nanjing China"}]},{"given":"Zi\u2010Kai","family":"Shao","sequence":"additional","affiliation":[{"name":"Department of Entomology Nanjing Agricultural University  Nanjing China"}]},{"ORCID":"http:\/\/orcid.org\/0000-0002-5209-3961","authenticated-orcid":false,"given":"Xiao\u2010Yue","family":"Hong","sequence":"additional","affiliation":[{"name":"Departm